# 🔍 Complete Enterprise Backend Audit Report
## Tenvo — Multi-Tenant, Multi-Domain Inventory + POS + ERP System

**Audit Date:** 2026-03-03  
**Auditor:** Antigravity AI — Senior Enterprise Architect  
**Codebase:** Next.js 16 + Prisma 7 + Supabase + BetterAuth  
**Schema Size:** 1,700 lines / 55 models  
**Backend Actions:** 37+ server actions across 4 plan tiers  

---

# PHASE 1: Architecture & System Design Analysis

## 1.1 Architecture Classification

| Aspect | Current State | Assessment |
|--------|---------------|------------|
| Pattern | **Modular Monolith** (Next.js App Router) | ✅ Appropriate for current scale |
| Backend | Next.js Server Actions (no separate API server) | ⚠️ Tight coupling to Next.js runtime |
| Database | PostgreSQL via Supabase (Neon-compatible) | ✅ Solid choice |
| ORM | Prisma 7 (schema) + Raw `pg` Pool (queries) | ⚠️ Dual data access — see finding below |
| Auth | BetterAuth with Prisma adapter | ✅ Modern, extensible |
| Multi-Tenancy | **Row-level isolation** via `business_id` | ✅ Correct for SaaS |
| Plan Tiers | 4 tiers: free → starter → professional → enterprise | ✅ Well-designed |

## 1.2 Module Dependency Map

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Server Actions] --> B[RBAC Guard]
    A --> C[pg Pool / Raw SQL]
    A --> D[Auth / BetterAuth]
    B --> E[Permissions Matrix]
    B --> F[Plan Feature Flags]
    A --> G[Services Layer]
    G --> H[AccountingService]
    G --> I[InventoryService]
    G --> J[BatchService]
    G --> K[AI Forecaster]
    G --> L[Workflow Engine]
    G --> M[Integration Engine]
    H --> A
    I --> A
```

## 1.3 Middleware Pipeline

| Layer | Implementation | Status |
|-------|---------------|--------|
| Authentication | `auth.api.getSession()` per action | ✅ Present |
| Business Authorization | `verifyBusinessAccess()` | ✅ Present |
| RBAC Permission Check | [hasPermission()](file:///c:/Users/zaliz/Downloads/APP_CHAT/financial-hub/lib/rbac/permissions.js#169-187) / [withGuard()](file:///c:/Users/zaliz/Downloads/APP_CHAT/financial-hub/lib/rbac/serverGuard.js#31-172) | ⚠️ Inconsistent usage |
| Plan Feature Guard | `checkPlanFeature()` / `planHasFeature()` | ✅ Present |
| Plan Limit Guard | `planWithinLimit()` | ✅ Present |
| Audit Logging | `auditWrite()` fire-and-forget | ⚠️ Not on all mutations |
| Rate Limiting | **MISSING** | 🔴 Critical gap |
| CSRF Protection | **MISSING** (Server Actions have some built-in) | ⚠️ Partial |

## 1.4 Critical Architecture Findings

### 🔴 CRITICAL: Dual Data Access Layer

The system uses **Prisma ORM for schema definition** but **raw `pg` Pool for all queries**. This creates:
- No compile-time type safety on queries
- No automatic relation loading
- Risk of SQL injection if string interpolation is ever used
- Schema-query drift (Prisma schema ≠ actual SQL column names)

**Evidence:** [pos.js](file:///c:/Users/zaliz/Downloads/APP_CHAT/financial-hub/lib/api/pos.js) line 32 references `terminal_name, terminal_code` but Prisma schema defines `name, code`.

> [!CAUTION]
> Column name mismatches between Prisma schema and raw SQL queries will cause runtime errors. Every raw query must be manually validated against the schema.

### 🔴 CRITICAL: Inconsistent Auth Guard Patterns

Three different auth guard patterns coexist:

| Pattern | Used In | Issues |
|---------|---------|--------|
| [withGuard()](file:///c:/Users/zaliz/Downloads/APP_CHAT/financial-hub/lib/rbac/serverGuard.js#31-172) | Newer actions (recommended) | ✅ Full 5-step enforcement |
| [checkAuth()](file:///c:/Users/zaliz/Downloads/APP_CHAT/financial-hub/lib/actions/basic/accounting.js#10-25) local | POS, Purchase actions | ⚠️ Missing RBAC permission checks |
| `verifyBusinessAccess()` direct | Legacy actions | ⚠️ No plan/feature/limit checks |

**Impact:** POS and Purchase actions bypass granular RBAC. A `viewer` role user who is a business member could potentially execute [createPosTransactionAction](file:///c:/Users/zaliz/Downloads/APP_CHAT/financial-hub/lib/actions/standard/pos.js#182-322).

### 🟡 WARNING: No Middleware Layer

Next.js `middleware.ts` is **absent**. All protection is applied per-action. This means:
- No global rate limiting
- No IP-based blocking
- No request logging at the edge
- No tenant context injection before route handlers

### 🟡 WARNING: No Event-Driven Architecture

All operations are synchronous. No message queue, no event bus. This means:
- Audit logging is fire-and-forget (can silently fail)
- No webhook dispatching
- No async notifications
- No retry mechanism for failed GL entries
- Stock deductions + GL entries in same transaction (increases lock contention)

### 🟢 POSITIVE: Clean Service Layer

Services (`AccountingService`, `InventoryService`, `BatchService`) provide a proper orchestration layer. The `AccountingService.recordBusinessTransaction()` bridge pattern for mapping business events to GL entries is well-designed.

